HEADWORD: Cursitor
<hw>Cur"si*tor</hw> <pr>(k?r"s?-t?r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>cursitor</ets>, equiv. to L. <ets>cursor</ets>, fr.
<ets>cursare</ets> to run hither and thither, fr. <ets>currere</ets> to
run. See <er>Current</er>, and cf. <er>Cursor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A courier or runner.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Cursitors</xex> to and fro.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eng.Law)</fld> <def>An officer in the Court of
Chancery, whose business is to make out original writs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cursive</ent>⟦br⟧
